Common Ground

We start by generating data using the mamba package.

# simulate data with mamba package
mamba_data <- generate_data_mamba()

# effect sizes and variance
snpeffect <- mamba_data$betajk
snpvar <- mamba_data$sjk2

Then we fit the simulated data to the mamba model.

# fitting simulated mamba data to model
if (file.exists("../test_data/sim_mod_mamba.rda")) {
  
  load(file = "../test_data/sim_mamba_mod.rda")
  
} else {
  
  sim_mod<-mamba(betajk = snpeffect, sjk2 = snpvar)
  save(sim_mod, file = "../test_data/sim_mamba_mod.rda")
  
}

# take values from model
pprs <- mod$ppr
effectsize <- mod$mu.hat
outliers <- mod$outliermat[ppr < 0.5]

For reference, a table of the SNPS and the probabilities of them being replicable is given below.

outliers

Well look at only the first SNP for now. The posterior-probability-of-replicability (PPR) for the first SNP is 0.0023025.

Our posterior predictive replication p-values (posterior PRP) for the first SNP using the PRP package is 0.763.

Quantitative/Qualitative Differences

Now we look at a few examples.

In the first case, we use a fake model with multiple with extreme outliers.

# high value nonzero effect size

fakesnp2 <- c(7, 8, 7, 5)
fakesnp3 <- c(7, 8, 7, 5)
fakesnpeffect <- rbind(fakesnp1, fakesnp2, fakesnp3)


# fake variance
fakesnpv1 <- c(3, 3, 3, 3)
fakesnpv2 <- c(4, 5, 5, 5)
fakesnpv3 <- c(4, 5, 5, 5)
fakesnpvar <- rbind(fakesnpv1, fakesnpv2, fakesnpv3)
fakemod1 <-mamba(betajk = fakesnpeffect, sjk2 = fakesnpvar)

In the second case, we generate a normal distribution with mean = 0 and standard deviation = 1.

Different Population Sampling

# allele sampling
n = 5000
allele0.01 <- rbinom(n, 2, 0.01)
allele0.1 <- rbinom(n, 2, 0.1)
allele0.25 <- rbinom(n, 2, 0.25)
epsilon <- rnorm(5000, mean = 0, sd = 0.0005)
beta = 0.005
y0.01 = (beta * allele0.01) + epsilon
y0.1 = (beta * allele0.1) + epsilon
y0.25 = (beta * allele0.25) + epsilon
lm_model0.01 <- lm(y0.01 ~ allele0.01)
bhat0.01 <- lm_model0.01$coefficients[2]

lm_model0.1 <- lm(y0.1 ~ allele0.1)
bhat0.1 <- lm_model0.1$coefficients[2]

lm_model0.25 <- lm(y0.25 ~ allele0.25)
bhat0.25 <- lm_model0.25$coefficients[2]
